    "summary": "The research for my master thesis (1970) and PhD thesis (1974) on magnetization distributions in nuclei was performed with the Electron Accelerator Amsterdam (EVA) at the former Institute for Nuclear-Physiscs Research in Amsterdam (IKO, later merged into Nikhef). During construction of the Medium Energy Accelerator (MEA) in Amsterdam, I continued the research on magnetization distributions at higher energies with the Acc\u00e9l\u00e9rateur lin\u00e9aire de Saclay (F), and was also project manager of the construction of the low-energy physics hall (LEF) at MEA.\n  In the eighties I was deputy programmme leader of the coincidence experiments with the two-spectrometer setup in the EMIN hall. With the technique of double-dispersion matching, which I developped, a nowhere improved energy resolution of 100 keV was achieved.\n  During the construction of the Amsterdam Pulse Stretcher (AmPS), which was the successor of MEA), I performed research at the accelerators in Lund (S) and Bonn (D). In the period of the experiments at AmPS I was programme leader of the research in the EMIN hall. This investigation was concluded with an experiment at the Mainz Microtron (MAMI) in collaboration with groups from Mainz and T\u00fcbingen (D), and Glasgow (UK). The last 10 years, I performed research on the spin structure of nucleons within the HERMES group at the HERA accelerator in Hamburg (D).\n  The investigations led to more than 150 publications in refereed journals and over 250 conference papers and scientific talks. I have experience in many aspects of scientific research in the field of nuclear physics and high energy physics, managed the research, was supervisor of master students and graduate students, active in various councils, and acted more than ten years (and still act) as chief editor of the Nikhef Annual Report.",
